,Not Recommended,224480,10889886,"Posted: 27 June, 2014",all,Paparazzi,"Octodad is the second game in the series, and Young Horses has had some time to hammer out and polish the big stuff - constraint physics, visual style, story - all the things that make it an indie darling. It's a short game (longer than DLC Quest but shorter than Portal) and for $15 you might argue you're not getting a lot. This game is fueled by quirkiness, relies on it, really, and its replay value depends on how efficiently you can convert its brand of humor into your personal brand of fun.I got a few laughs out of it, but also a few frustrations. For the buildup to the final boss you're tossed into an irresponsibly designed level of precision platforming, bad camera, and a floor that falls under your feet with very little conveyance. This is a massive contrast to the rest of the game with its open environments and reliance of a more-or-less static world. I got stuck in the world geometry more than I'd care to admit there, but think of it less as a nitpick and more as indicative of the overall game - I feel the developers got a fun toy (constraint physics), decided to wrap a one-off around it, and ran out of ideas. I really do think this game was intended to be $15 worth of game-hours but they had to piece together what they had and sell it.Like I said, I'm hard pressed to find $15 of value here. I didn't try co-op nor go for some of ""advanced"" achievements but I don't think it would have rocketed this game to a glowing recommendation."
