,Recommended,224480,8946403,"Posted: 2 February, 2014",all,R0AHN,"The first time I saw this game on the front page of Steam my thoughts went pretty much like this:""Okay, is this some sort of 'ironic' take on Octomom and Deadliest Catch? @#$%ing hipsters.""I don't even remember why I clicked on it. First impressions can make or break a game's selling potential and I know I can't be alone in this sort of off-the-shelf assessment. Such cynicism doesn't do this game justice.The control scheme makes it unique and is the true core of gameplay - the adventure game key puzzles would be the spokes on that particular wheel. Some people may allude to ""to walk forward you alternate between pressing L1 and R1"" (thank you Yahtzee) and... well, the trailer showcases exactly how chaotic this is. It works better than it sounds, a description which sums up this game quite well.It's a rare game that is actually funny in its own quirky way, and not by the usual use of 'ironic' references. The entire premise is preposterous but the characters are endearing and the developers included their message without having to shovel in hours of exposition. The length is just right for a game of its tyle in that it doesn't become tiresome or run out of steam halfway through. Overall it all blends together into a game is simultaneously one that I recommend but I can think of no good way to market to a developer. You could say it's an ideal example of how Steam is a great platform for the independent developer to put out quality material on the market."
