,Recommended,224480,11365561,"Posted: 22 July, 2014",all,albertrayon,"Octodad: Dadliest Catch is a game where you play a completely normal, everyday dad pretending to be an octopus. You must perform mundane tasks to take care of your family, while escaping from a sushi chef who can hold quite the grudge.The control scheme in Octodad is where the real meat of this game is. You can control one arm and both legs by utilizing all sticks and triggers on a gamepad. I'm not sure if mouse and keyboard is supported, but I think using that would take away from some of the fun. You will really have to utilize all your concentration and hand-eye coordination to move with Octodad. Even in the endgame I was still getting frustrated at times just trying to move around, but that's pretty much the whole point of the game. There's plenty of leeway for when you need to manipulate objects, thankfully. Each level has a checkpoint system, so if you fail, which will probably happen a few times, you go right back to the beginning of the latest objective and don't lose too much progress.Octodad: Dadliest Catch is pretty short, and can be beaten in maybe 90 minutes. Most of the levels are entertaining enough that you will want to try them again, either to beat your previous best time or to find collectables and unlock achievements. A lot of fun can be had by seeing how much of a jerk you can be with the physics in all the levels. This game has workshop support, which will add some replayability to the game as well. The graphics are very cartoonish, and work well with the story and whole idea of the game.Octodad: Dadliest Catch was very enjoyable for the time that it lasted on my runthrough. I wish it was a little longer, but Workshop support is there if I feel the need to play more levels. Still, the devs could have added a little more to make this a longer experience. I will definitely go back to it from time to time and see how I could have completed the levels differently. I would recommend this game, but keep in mind that it will take more than one playthrough to get your money's worth.Grade: B"
