76561198123663421,Recommended,224480,9708467,"Posted: 2 April, 2014",all,Tairy Greene,"Octodads witty humor, willing challenge, and utter pointlessness is it's strongest traits. For the most part, the game is certainly enjoyable, especially when purchased on sale. While the two dollars may not seem like it can make or break a game (and for many it wouldn't) those of you who are taking the time to read reviews are likely doing it to be sure you aren't wasting your money.  I digress.Octodad: Dadliest Catch is as ammusing as it is a challenge. (At least as far as I have done playing on a mouse and keyboard.) I personally got it on sale for ten dollars and felt satisfied only when I browsed the already bustleing workshop filled with bonus levels and such.In my opinion, I would suggest this game, however silly it may be."
,Recommended,224480,10921648,"Posted: 28 June, 2014",all,megarust,Funny.
,Recommended,224480,8962908,"Posted: 3 February, 2014",all,HWECQI,"I originally played Octodad when it was a small, free game made by some college students. It was absolutely hilarious and it was a very unique concept. So, when I heard that they had a Kickstarter I was super excited! I was very glad to see them get the funding they needed.Octodad: Dadliest Catch is the fruit of the Young Horses team's efforts, and I was not disappointed. This is a game similar to QWOP and Surgeon Simulator in that the difficulty of the controls is part of the charm. You control Octodad by independently clicking and dragging each limb around to walk, and you can switch to your arm tentacles to grab things. It takes some getting used to for sure, but it is always a joy to see you flop around and decimate an entire room while people watch you, completely unaware that you are an octopus in a suit.This game conveys a lot through it's gameplay, which is something that is kind of rare to find nowadays. The gameplay augments everything that is there, and it really makes you feel like someone trying to fit in but having a really difficult time of doing so. When things get rough, you can really feel the tension in the situation as you try to scramble your way to safety.I recommend this game highly, however I had some gripes with it, which are mostly technical.I found myself sometimes getting caught on the physics, like I would try to climb something or move out of a bathroom stall and Octodad would get wedged in the floor or in the wall. Granted, this is something to be expected of a character that is constantly ragdolled and puppeteered, but it can definitely be aggrivating.I also found the game would hang frequently. This isn't an issue of my hardware being up to snuff either, as my machine is fairly powerful and I can play more graphically intensive games with no problem. This is probably due to some poor optimization and the constant physics simulation. It sometimes made it annoying to playthrough.The Story is also pretty short, I was able to complete it within 2 hours. The game isn't too expensive however so this is a bit more excusable, but you may want to wait for a sale, as this is probably better suited for the $5 price range. It is worth noting however that there is also Steam Workshop support and a full fledged tool to make your own Octodad levels. It's kind of awesome, though there hasn't been much content made for it yet. If you are interested in this kind of thing though you might find yourself occupied for quite some time.Despite these problems though, Octodad is a really charming, fun, and unforgettable experience."
