,Recommended,224480,9495695,"Posted: 15 March, 2014",all,Zephyr,"So first thing I'm gonna say is that this game is just absolutely stupid. It's funny, it's great, but if you're not a fan of slapstick humour, you won't find half of the humour in this game funny.Octodad: Dadliest Catch is an... interesting game just to say the least. You play an octopus disguised as a human with a family. It's like, what? But, miraculously, it still makes a great game. The co-op feature in this game is absolutely hilarious. That's where most of my 4 hours of this game have went so far with friends. Characters are great, level design is great, and it's quite hard to hate. There are quite a few glitches too, but nothing that breaks the game.I finished the story with a very satisfied feeling, apart from the fact they don't explain at all where Tommy and Stacy come from...The only thing about this game is that it's very, very short. Unlike a huge title game, the campaign is very short. You can finish it in about an hour and a half, and, if you know what you're doing, probably under an hour.  Imagine all the other situations Octodad could get into! Imagine if he had to drive his kids to school? Imagine if he needed to go to a meeting? There are so many things that could have happened, but didn't.Really, my opinion is, if you're willing to pay $15 for a game that will provide with some humour, tortorus co-op and some Community Workshop items, buy this game. You won't regret, and there'll be at least one reference you didn't see in the first time playing. (e.g. In the shopping level, there's a type of pie that's called ""Pewdie Pie."" Genius.) But, if you're buying to get hours and hours out of the campaign, online multiplayer and other things from a big budget game, don't buy this game, because you'll be disappointed. I'm just a sort of person that likes creative games, and this is pretty creative, considering you have to do daily dad stuff as an octopus. Find me another game like that and you'll get $100.Workshop levels are also insane fun, like making zero gravity Octodad and 'Wrecking Blub.' Not sure if you wanna know but find out for yourself.In short, Octodad: Dadliest Catch is worth the money if it's your sort of game, but if you hate short campaigns and what not, but you still want to get the game, wait for a Steam sales to rob your wallet to buy this game.I'm going to give this game a 8/10"
