,Recommended,224480,15820000,"Posted: 13 May, 2015",all,Waffle King,"Hey, I Think I Saw This In A Porno Once-An Official Waffle King Review~Find morehere.Parenthood is truly a magical experience. Creating life, loving and caring for it, and helping it to grow into a real live person just like yourself. It often gets a bad reputation in most media, unfortunately. No one WANTS kids, kids just HAPPEN. And they're just hell spawn. It's much better to stay singe and childless forever... or so they say.Fatherhood, while many are often chosen for the job, it's the ones that choose it that are the real heroes. The ones unafraid to raise a child, to make someone else the main focus of their life besides themselves, and ultimately make as many dad jokes as humanly possible. It's the dad code, the unwritten laws passed through the fatherhood of the dads. Not all are fit to rise to the challenge. Some are unfit. Some are thrown into it unwillingly. And some... some are octopi.You have not experienced being a dad until you've been an octopus. Are you an octopus?Octodad: Dadliest Catch, currently on PS4 and PC and soon coming to Wii U and Xbox One, is the touching tale of a dad. It's full of action, drama, suspense, and the endless love of fatherhood. Also, tentacles. Those are great.You are a dad. That's right, just a perfectly normal, average dad. You must do everyday, normal dad things. Making coffee, mowing the lawn, grilling burgers, and taking the family to the supermarket to get groceries.However, later in the game, over the course of many twists and turns in the constantly thickening plot... it's revealed...SPOILER ALERT.FOR REAL, SPOILERS, THIS WILL RUIN THE GAME FOR YOUHE'S ACTUALLY AN OCTOPUS.It's something you would never see coming, the kind of plot twist that just seems nonsensical and wrong on so many levels. But it's there. They did it. They truly have no shame, stooping so low as to turn a game about fatherhood into some crazy, wacky game with a gimmicky twist. What is this, Game of Thrones?Dadliest Catch is a fantastic game, and yet only as appealing as how you feel about the game's premise. It's a wonky physics game. Like someone made QWOP into a full game. You'll control Octodad's tentacles, which are used as crude arms and legs. And that's pretty much the game. There's not all that much more to it than that.The controls are the challenge, essentially. Trying to QWOP your way through an average day in the life of a dad. Stumbling awkwardly through rooms, knocking things over and slipping on conveniently placed banana peels. It's not meant to be a serious game at all. As if the premise itself was not evident enough of that.The concept itself was what drew me to the game, and the masterful execution on such a ridiculous concept was what gave it a special place in my heart. If you can enjoy the sheer hilarity of dumping chocolate milk on a little girl's head as you struggle to pour her a drink, this is the game for you.The level design is perfectly done. Each level has little challenges to overcome, and they're all thought out so cleverly. There are no recycled bits that weigh down the action. And how funny each scenario is only makes each one better. As the levels go on, the underlying stealth elements begin to ramp up. If you goof around too much in public, people might start thinking you're an octopus.The stealth elements are really not the best part of the game. It's not a fun sneaking game, mostly because simply getting from Point A to Point B is difficult enough. But the stealth never really takes over the majority of the gameplay. There's one mainly stealth mission, and it's not particularly difficult. None of the stealth portions really are. The characters you need to sneak around pretty much face a single direction indefinitely for the most part.Unlike something like QWOP, Octodad is trying to be a real game. It definitely ramps up in difficulty, and the final level is as brutal as it is ridiculous and epic. And yet even its most dramatic of moments are goofy and light-hearted.Octodad is a joke. It's not hard to figure that much out. But it's a very in-depth joke. Its underlying sense of humor and the surprisingly wide range of emotions it can convey really make the game. You'll laugh, but you'll also feel something for Octodad. He's more than a wonky gimmick character. He IS a wonky gimmick character, but he's been fleshed out to be more. He's not even the only entertaining character. The writing seems to perfectly capture the feeling of a family sitcom. Octodad's loving wife and kids are cute and endearingly funny. You start to feel invested in them, and in Octodad's adventure. I'll tell you what, going into this, feeling empathy or sympathy for Octodad was not something I was expecting. The ludicrous amount of banana peels and QWOPing around the supermarket, I saw that coming. But the feels? Those were a nice surprise. Surprise feels are the best kind of feels. Especially when they include tentacles.Wait... No, yeah, I meant what I said.I must say, the PC version definitely seems to be the definitive one to play. While it's much better to play with a controller, the console versions are missing the level editor. Which adds quite a bit more meat to a fairly short game.Regardless, no matter what you're playing it on, it's definitely worth playing. It's not an edgy, serious game with post-apocalyptic zombie mech assassins or anything. It's not a rogue-like, there's no RPG mechanics, there's no heated PvP deathmatch. But it's a game about a mother♥♥♥♥ing octopus in a suit.How can you not find some shred of enjoyment in this? What are you, Satan after a do-it-yourself vasectomy? Did you just finish washing your bloody pair of safety scissors? Octodad is just fun, plain and simple. It just is. And not only is it fun, but it makes you feel good on the inside. Like playing in a ball pit full of puppies.I feel like maybe I've learned a lesson from Octodad. Maybe being a father isn't such a terrifying thing. It's a commitment, yeah. A big one. But if it means I get to throw raw meat at my kids and have tentacle sex with my wife, I'm sure it'd be worth it.Now if only there was a girl interested in being impregnated by tentacles...To the internet!"
