76561198056879077,Recommended,224480,10167148,"Posted: 18 May, 2014",all,pickles4nickles,"Octodad is... kind of a weird game. And not just because, well, you know, the whole octopus masquerading as a human thing.If you're looking for something innovative that will blow your mind, Octodad isn't the game for you, but if you're just looking for something small and relaxing to play, you should try it out. The game plays like QWOP meets the SPORE Galactic Adventures expansion pack. The game feels kinda fetch quest-y, but that's not necessarily a bad thing as it didn't get tiring for me.The main gimmick of Octodad is your inability to use your limbs like a normal human being, therefore, the controls are kinda wonky. As someone who's played the original student project Octodad, I didn't have too much problems with the controls, but to new players, the rhythm of the controls might be hard to grasp.Octodad's biggest strength is its story. It's simple, quirky, and will warm your heart... or weird you out, take your pick. Because of this, the game feels more like an interactive movie than a full-blown video game, which, again, isn't a bad thing. Considering a movie ticket is about ten bucks or so for matinee, on sale, and the story mode will take about two to three hours to finish Octodad's not a terrible deal. It's a very light game with a lighthearted story that'll make you feel happy."
