76561197980107643,Recommended,224480,9087328,"Posted: 13 February, 2014",all,Flailsnail,"Octodad: Dadliest CatchOctodad: Dadliest Catch is something of a mouthful. It is also something of an absurdity. This is a game that places you in the shoes (literally) of an octopus. An octopus who is desperately trying to pass himself off as a normal human being against all odds. But does the insanity equate to fun, or is it just a temporary distraction? A lasting entertainment or something to be forgotten? Let’s take a look.As the Octodad, your job is to hide your true octopus identity from your wife, your kids, and the rest of the human race. See, they don’t take kindly to aquatic life pretending to be people in this world. They would much rather catch and eat your octopus butt. The way you go about this is to act as normal as possible and go about your everyday activities. Mow the lawn, weed the garden, do some shopping at the local grocery. All of the things a normal human father would do. The catch, of course, is that you have tentacles, and not hands or feet. Tentacles with powerful suction cups attached. As a result every action you take is an exercise in insanity. Chopping firewood ends with you wildly swinging an axe around in hopes of striking wood. Shopping involves taking big loping steps around the grocery store trying not to knock every shelf in the store down around you. It is equal parts entertainment and frustration.Blending in to human society is as easy as not acting suspicious when you can be seen. Every pedestrian, every police officer, even your own family observe your actions. So of course barreling through the grocery store knocking everything over results in suspicion and mistrust. You must manage that suspicion lest your true octopus identity be discovered. Never mind how you have children in the first place without your wife knowing the truth. That’s an issue I don’t intend to go into great detail about. We’ll also ignore, for the sake of suspension of disbelief, the fact that you very clearly have an octopus head and tentacles and there is no way to deny it! Those two things aside, blending in is a relatively simple task; don’t knock over everything in sight, try not to get ink everywhere, and don’t glob on to anyone’s face. Not so hard, right?The graphics and sound are suitably adorable. The humans are all fully voice acted while Octodad communicates via burbles and glug noises. They will likely make you smile despite yourself, and should be applauded for their comic value. Visually it’s simple, with its comic inspired appearance and pleasant suburban setting. Yet it fits incredibly well, somehow. It invokes a remarkable feeling of accomplishment for completing even the most simple of tasks. There is joy in successfully chopping firewood, pleasure in navigating a shopping mall without causing complete destruction, and happiness in making your family unit smile simply by the act of trying to be a human. If that’s not some kind of hidden message the developers intentionally meant for us to realize, then I don’t know what is. Maybe I’m just crazy. In fact, that is a distinct possibility.Whatever the case, the game has a certain kind of joyful appeal in its simplicity. Give it a shot. You might just find something you thoroughly enjoy."
