76561198123383418,Recommended,224480,8922749,"Posted: 31 January, 2014",all,Snail,"I love this game! I've been waiting for this game for some months now, and I bought it the first day it came out.Is it perfect?...Nooooo?Oh, don't get me wrong, this game is awesome!Let's get onto the controls, anyone who has played the original student game knows that the controls are very awkward. And in this game they're awkward, too. But the major difference is that the first game was very buggy, and many issues could came up depending on your computer's performance (in my case Octodad would begin to climb towards the sky and then slowly come back to the ground). This is not the case in Dadliest Catch. The controls are still very awkward, but there are no real issues with them. They're smooth. Weird, but smooth.Now let's get to the graphics. They're really fun, too! I adore the cartoony feel the game has. It's no surprise Octodad could get into our society, everyone has bug eyes! They remind me a bit of Garfield cartoons. They're not the highest qualiy, but they're not terrible, either. They're not even close to being bad.And now, the story. Oh, man, I love the story. It has to be my favorite feature of the game. I won't spoil anything for those who haven't bought the game yet, but let's just say it balances humor with a dash of emotion. Throughout the whole game, everything is full of very funny jokes and missions that you have to complete.Then the game will get emotional. I was already expecting some sad moments, but nothing like this, actually! The characters are very well written. Even Octodad has many character-defining moments. And the relationships with him and his wife and children are adorable.The voice acting is also really good, too. And it helps to make the story even better.Well, now that we ran across the good, let's run over the bad.This game is too short.Plain and simple, I'm not going to blame the devs, though. This is their first comercial release, and overall it's really solid, so they get a pass. But still, the game feels too short. Most of the time the only reason the game will be longer for you is because you keep dying or because you try to make every single task longer on your own. Sometimes I also feel that the briefness of the game may affect the story a bit. Sure, I praised the story earlier, but the overall briefness of the game opened new questions about the universe this game takes place in.However, there are still somethings you can do. You can go back to the levels you have beaten and attempt to collect all the ties, or maybe even beat the devs records for finishing the levels. But after that, the game is pretty much done. I don't know if unlocking all the ties or beating the devs' records will unlock anything, though. I haven't done that.Thankfully though, the game is hilarious all the way through, even if the briefness makes it a teensy little bit dissapointing. Besides, the game supports Steam Workshop, so you can expect many crazy mods in the future made by fans (and maybe even Young Horses themselves) to fill up the space.Overall, I give this game a 9 out of 10! Do I recommend it? You bet your tentacles I do!Well, review over, now please excuse me while I go and fangirl all over my new OTP. ;w;"
,Recommended,224480,8922791,"Posted: 31 January, 2014",all,Sketchbored,"This Game is very wacky and is charming in it's own ways. Even though it's not that long ( I beat it in 3-2 hours) and their isn't much content to come back to, other than the achievements and tie collecting ( There is also a octodad level editor in the game files to make your own levels and publish them to the workshop, but you may have to get used to the editor for a while to get the hang of it), you get wacky controls, hilarious movements, and being a father and an octopus at the same time, with nobody knowing you aren't really a human. What's not to love about it?!"
