76561198040215860,Recommended,224480,8920329,"Posted: 31 January, 2014",all,@TheRealJordanRodkey,"For the first hour of the game, Octodad: Dadliest Catch is what Octodad should be. Awkward prop manipulation and casual/fun (did I mention awkward?) exploration. Any sort of challenge (outside the intentional flimsyness) is modest enough to not get in the way, but prevelent enough to give the game some welcomed tension (see: the sparse sets of marine biologists, who are simply more prone to suspicion than the average bystander).Then the game suddenly becomes much more about strict platforming/stealth challenges, completely missing the point of why this franchise is so interesting and fun. Outside the very final section, the game still retains plenty of charm, but it never again reaches the level of fun had in the the supermarket or the initial aquarium sections. If the game was solely about stuff like that, this would've been one of my new favorite games. However, it's briefness in it's truly fun and genius level design is what's ultimately it's biggest issue.There's a difference between a game like Journey, which was completely fleshed out and properly paced for as simple of an idea as it was... and a game like Octodad, which is just as long, but still holds a tremendous amount of potential (Hell, they wouldn't have implemented Steam Workshop if it wasn't true).I can't help but feel they have chosen to rely primarily on Steam Workshop to make this game anywhere near fully realized. Which is especially irking after an already very successful community-centric Kickstarter. WE CAN'T DO EVERYTHING GUYS! After 2 and a half years of development from a team well aware of the game's expectations to be a lot more than it's previous tech demo, it's a huge disappointment in at least one respect.But, despite the cynicism, the game is some of the most fun you'll ever have in video games for it's first hour... and all that Workshop content will be ""free"". So it's a recommendation."
