,Recommended,224480,18078999,"Posted: 17 September, 2015",all,HeWhosKnownAsIAm,"Lets be clear right off the bat.This game was not made for any reason other than to be laughed at by streamers and youtubers.That being said, this game takes a youtube fodder premise and turned it into a competent cohesive game. There is a story that is both funny and makes sense (in the context of the game of course) and makes jokes beyond ""HAHA look that silly thing happened ona'counta the wacky controls"". Goat Simulator or I Am Bread this is not.You play as Octo-Dad. A regular, normal, everyday, run of the mill, white bread dad. DId I mention he's normal? The game really drives that joke home. You control a single limb at a time, each limb consisting of two tentacles stuck together. The joke of the game which is pretty much the central focus being clumsily moving around trying not to raise suspision while you do normal dad things like pouring milk in your daughters glass, mowing the lawn while avoiding flowers, or sneaking past ravenous sushi chefs hell bent on killing and cooking you.This would wear thin if they did the Goat Simulator thing of making a big map and calling it a sandbox while adding no actual gameplay. Thankfully this game is anything but a sandbox. It's actually quite linear, with clear and varried goals that move you along a fairly funny story about the previously mentioned chef trying to kill you, you getting lost in an aquarium, and trying to make it back to your family. It's no Shakespear but it has a clear story to tell and uses the medium effectivly to do so. The story is advanced by the gameplay, not the other way around. This works very well to keep what would otherwise be a 10 minute game, interesting.It even had a pretty fun multiplayer mode where each player controls a different limb or side of the body. It is actually a lot more fun than it sounds.It's one of those games you need to just play to get. Im sure its super fun to watch others play (it was desgined with this in mind afterall) but nothing compares to actually playing it.One last thing, this game supports touch screens and is a blast to play on windows tablet PCs like the surface pro, I actually feel like you have far better control than with the M&K or a controller. Not alot of games support touch, which is odd considering laptops outnumber desktop PCs like 10 to 1, and most new laptops come with touch screens. Neat little bonus."
,Recommended,224480,18073275,"Posted: 17 September, 2015",all,spook zone,blub
,Recommended,224480,18085062,"Posted: 18 September, 2015",all,Saph,"Octodad: Deadliest Catch is what I hope for in most indie titles I purchase, it builds from something I used to play on some site during break at school. Of course I'm talking about QWOP, a game I had a lot of fun practising but never mastering.You control Octodad, the protagonist of the game as he desperately attempts to stumble his way through several zany environments while avoiding suspition. Should his cover be blown it's game over and you get thrown back to the last checkpoint.The gameplay itself is very simple, however as I already said it really feels like it built from the concept of games like QWOP. Even going so far as to reference it at one point. However unlike QWOP the controls are fairly easy to grasp and in turn they give the game a unique charm that really enthralled me as the player. There are even some pretty clever puzzles thrown in there too, nothing too brain racking but clever nonetheless.Something about walking down the aisle whilst avoiding banana peels, pots on pedestals and the temptation to start breakdancing for everybody attending is just so lovely and gives the game a fantastic appeal that will at the very least drive you to beat it. Even if you only do so to experience more of the clever nautical humour.For you completionists out there, there are even hidden collectible ties hidden within each level that will take some real dedication and thinking outside the box to find. This is just a side thing and I personally didn't go for them intentionally, but the ones I did find and manage to reach felt pretty satisfying to collect.Octodad is a very lighthearted and silly game that is suitable for all the family. A must buy for your kids and a must play if you enjoy cartoonish settings reminiscent of shows like Tom & Jerry with a pinch of (kid friendly) James Bond movies added to the mix."
