76561197983662248,Recommended,224480,11233832,"Posted: 14 July, 2014",all,TechieRefugee,"To start: I used to add a header to these reviews, but since it made the reviews too long to submit sometimes, I decided to leave it on my Backloggery.Gameplay: Octodad's main gimmick is the controls, but not in a bad way. You can get used to it pretty quickly, and for those who have played the original freeware Octodad, nothing much has really changed. You control Octodad mainly with the mouse while controlling the camera with WASD. You don't have free range with respect to controlling the camera like you did in the freeware game, but there may be an option that allows you to have full control of the camera somewhere. Nevertheless, the camera angles chosen by the game were plenty good enough for me to do what I had to do.As you'd expect from the ""full version"" of the game, you get to do a lot more within the levels. Some of the jokes like banana peels being infernal hellspawn may be lost on those who haven't played the first game, but they're still a classic slapstick gag. Anyways, the areas within the game encourage some degree of exploration, with the main collectable of the game being ties being hidden throughout most every level. I didn't bother to get all the ties on my first playthrough, but I will do that in the future. There's also a lot more platforming within these levels, although not exactly like the final level from the first game. It's a lot of fun just trying to do simple things like climbing wrong-way escalators and ladders.That's a lot of the emphasis of the game's design: making simple things very difficult, yet still fun to do. It does succeed in that. Now, the game is rather short; I only spent about two hours just playing through the game at my pace. I'd imagine I could've spent another couple of hours hunting around for ties. Steam Workshop is available for this game, although there isn't too terribly large a swathe of levels available. Nevertheless, it is a very welcome addition. As far as the gameplay goes, if you liked the original Octodad, you'll like this game. If you didn't like the original, you won't like this. If you're not sure or haven't played either, get the original and see how you feel about it. I feel like it's the kind of game that can stay fresh with a yearly playthrough or something. 8/10.Story: As far as the actual plot goes, subtracting all the humor, it's not bad. It gives a neat little backstory as to how Octodad came to be and it gives a pretty satisfying ending. Add the humor in, and it sure becomes a story (deadpan). You'll definitely get a lot of laughs out of this game. I'm not gonna spoil any of it, but what I can say is that it's like taking a Hannah-Barbara cartoon and adding in liberal amounts of octopus. So if you like that kind of pacing and presentation, you'll get a kick out of this game. 8/10.Graphics: Yet another thing that fits in with that sorta Hannah-Barbara motif. It's very cartoonish and very nice to look at. All of the areas are very bright and vivid with a great bit of art direction. It's basically the style of the original Octodad kicked up a notch and brought into the current year. Even still, I'd say that this game will still look pretty rad, even in a decade or so. Even the original Octodad still looks pretty good today, and that was a school project. As far as the technical details, I was able to kick it up to 1080p at max settings without any hassle on my GTX 760. It stayed at a very consistent 60FPS, with a couple of lag spots here and there (I'm not really sure why the spots that lagged did so) and ran very cool, topping out with a temperature of 52degC. It looks great and it runs easy on your computer. What more could you want? 5/5.Sound: Octodad has the best voice actor of all time. Everybody else... well, it doesn't need to be too dramatic. We are talking about something along the lines of a Hannah-Barbara cartoon, after all. Anyways, the sound direction for this game is most certainly comedic and can often times be the main contributor to the humor of the situation. It's definitely a game where playing it without sound would take away a lot of the enjoyment. The music is pretty fun as well, with the main theme being a highlight. Again, the music is decidedly absurd, which is only apropos given the scenario. I'd play the game first, and if you end up digging the soundtrack, I'd pick it up. It's good enough to do that for. 5/5.Overall scores are: 8/8/5/5; cumulative score of 8.7/10. While it may have been pretty short, what was there was excellent stuff. Again, I'd play the original to see how you feel about buying this. I picked it up on sale ($7.50, I think?), and I feel like I'll get my value out of it from future playthroughs. It's definitely a game that allows for that."
76561198039223522,Recommended,224480,11237370,"Posted: 14 July, 2014",all,aieousavren,"Very fun game, with interesting controls. Well, by interesting, I mean if you're not good at them, you'll probably scream :D However, whether you get good at them or not, it's sure to be funny. OctoDad, obviously, is an octopus, and as such flips all over the place in a very amusing manner. Workshop support is fun, and works well, allowing you to play other people's levels. The humor (he writing, I mean) is top-notch, and well executed. Not very long, but still definitely worth the money, especially since you can work on achievements after you finish the game."
