,Recommended,224480,11321180,"Posted: 19 July, 2014",all,Mnemophage,"At the crux of the evening, the house is blazing with light. The living room television is blaring a violently fast cartoon, all primary colors and product placement, into the wide and waiting eyes of a hunched little boy. The children's bedroom is a mass of desk lamps and paper scraps as a thick-fingered young girl carefully cuts out paper dolls, each inch of clearance given with utmost care. In the kitchen, the mother sits over a newspaper crossword, the evening's final cup of coffee growing cool and thick in a hand-painted kindergarten mug. Talk radio is blaring, filling up the empty room with insipid local news, distant international tumults, arcane sports scores, quarter-hour traffic reports.All this light and sound and activity almost covers the gaping hole in the center of the household. The woman's mug has a partner, still sitting in the draining board, untouched for what feels like years. Two depressions in the living room couch, one steadily filling, marks where the heavier adults would sit, watching their children watch. The boy clutches an action figure in his hands - there is no one there to play the bad guys anymore. The girl squirts glue up the wallpaper, but leaves it, untouched - there is no one there to care about the mess. The woman reaches up to turn down a sudden piece of jazz, but remembers - there is no longer anyone in the household who minds that discordant tune.It may be years before the family acknowledges that crater in the center of their lives. Absurd machismo; a string of bad boyfriends; a slow habit grown one glass of wine a night - each may try, inexpertly, to fill that hole. When they finally speak of it, it may be years later - maybe at another graveside, maybe as some long-remembered birthday passes, maybe suddenly and with no provocation at all. Maybe they will speak of it, but they will never be rid of it. They will always remember the father who loved them, and now the father that  is gone.And several blocks away, your takoyaki arrives. It is cruchy and reasonably priced. You might consider a tip, or a good review online."
